Git Tutorial and Clean Code Guidelines
Overview

This project aims to provide a comprehensive guide to using Git effectively while adhering to principles of Clean Code. Whether you're a beginner or an experienced developer, this tutorial will walk you through the basics of Git and provide insights into writing clean, maintainable code.
Git Tutorial
Getting Started

If you're new to Git, start by installing Git on your system. You can download it from the official Git website. Once installed, you can initialize a new Git repository in your project directory using the git init command.
Basic Commands

    git add: Add files to the staging area.
    git commit: Record changes to the repository.
    git push: Push local changes to a remote repository.
    git pull: Fetch changes from a remote repository and merge them into the local branch.
    git clone: Clone a repository into a new directory.

Branching and Merging

    git branch: List, create, or delete branches.
    git checkout: Switch branches or restore working tree files.
    git merge: Merge changes from one branch into another.
    git rebase: Reapply commits on top of another base tip.

Collaboration

    Forking repositories
    Pull requests
    Code reviews

Clean Code Guidelines

Writing clean, maintainable code is essential for the long-term success of any project. Here are some guidelines to follow:

    Meaningful Names: Use descriptive names for variables, functions, and classes.
    Modularization: Break down your code into smaller, reusable modules.
    Simplicity: Keep your code simple and easy to understand.
    Comments: Use comments to explain complex logic or why certain decisions were made.
    Consistency: Follow consistent coding conventions throughout your project.
    Testing: Write tests to ensure the correctness of your code.
    Refactoring: Continuously refactor your code to improve its design and readability.

Contributing

Contributions to this project are welcome! If you have any suggestions, improvements, or bug fixes, feel free to open an issue or submit a pull request.
